<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-726-676  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 726 676.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Oct 2 1989 v6 n39 p5(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>PageMaker for OS/2: fast and flexible. (Software Review)(evaluation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lewallen, Dale.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Aldus Corp's PageMaker for OS/2 version 3.0 takes advantage ofOS/2's multitasking features to perform faster than its Windowsand Macintosh counterparts.andP;  Developers can take advantage of theway the program implements the multithreading feature to makeportions of their programs run simultaneously in the background.andO;m Operations such as loading and placement of text, printing, andscreen repainting take place in the background, saving time forusers.andP;  Up to four documents can be open simultaneously, each in aseparate window.andP;  The Smart ASCII filter lets users strip extracarriage returns from a document and convert extra spaces to tabs.andO;Only a PostScript device driver is available at this point, but aLaserJet driver is expected by the end of 1989.andP;  PageMaker forOS/2 lists for $795.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Aldus Corp. (product introduction).andO;Ticker:    ALDC.andO;Product:   PageMaker for OS/2 3.0 (Computer program).andO;Topic:     Computer GraphicsProduct IntroductionSoftware packagesDesktop publishing.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Dale LewallenandM;Lending support to the adage &quot;Time is money,&quot; Aldus Corp. has made good witha speedy version 3.0 of PageMaker for OS/2.andM;The new software, which the Seattle firm began shipping last week, takesadvantage of OS/2's multitasking features and performs faster than itsWindows and Macintosh siblings.andM;Aldus has done its homework, accomplishing more than a mere port of itsflagship product to OS/2.andM;PageMaker for OS/2 works faster because of the way Aldus has implemented themultithreading feature of the operating system; developers can writeapplications so that portions of the program -- threads -- can runsimultaneously in the background.andM;PageMaker for OS/2 implements multithreading in several key areas.andO;Operations such as the loading and automatic placement of text, screenrepainting and printing all occur in the background.andP;  As a result, users willspend less time waiting for these operations.andM;OS/2 allows for other special operations as well.andP;  For example, it is nowpossible to open as many as four documents, each in a separate window, asopposed to only one under the Windows and Macintosh versions.andP;  Files createdwith the OS/2 version are completely compatible with files created with theWindows and Macintosh versions.andM;Users who download information from company mainframes will find the additionof a special filter -- called &quot;Smart ASCII&quot; -- especially helpful.andP;  Amongother things, the filter lets users strip extra carriage returns from adocument and convert extra spaces to tabs.andP;  Also, with the release of OS/21.2, support for IBM's GDDM mainframe graphics files has been added.andM;PC Week tested PageMaker for OS/2 on a 20MHz 386 PC with 4M bytes of RAMrunning Dell Computer Corp.'s OS/2 1.1 and Microsoft Windows/386.andP;  Operationssuch as automatic text flow, graphics placement, printing and screen redrawswere tested.andM;Some minor problems exist, however, and they are mostly due to currentlimitations of OS/2.andP;  For example, PageMaker for OS/2 is constrained by thelack of a consistent screen-font imaging model for all OS/2 applications.andO;Apple Computer Inc. and Microsoft Corp.'s recent technology-sharing agreementwill address this issue in the future.andM;To make up for this, Aldus has added screen fonts -- such as Palatino andAvant Garde -- to those included with OS/2.andM;Also, PageMaker provides only a PostScript device driver; it does not includedrivers for Hewlett-Packard Co.'s LaserJet printers.andP;  Aldus, however, was notresponsible for driver development, and the lack of drivers is a problemcommon to all OS/2 applications.andP;  A LaserJet driver is expected by year'send.andM;PageMaker for OS/2, like the Windows version, can import a wide variety offile formats.andP;  While support for Lotus 1-2-3 and dBASE has not been includedin the OS/2 version now available, Aldus plans to support them.andM;PageMaker for OS/2 costs $795.andP;  Users of the Windows version can upgrade for$95.andO;</TEXT></DOC>